Exercise 13.6: What is a copy-assignment operator? When is this operator
used? What does the synthesized copy-assignment operator do? When is it
synthesized?

Answer:
Copy-assignment operator is a member function: operator= which takes an argument of the class type and it
controls how object are being copied.

This operator is called when assigning.
synthesized copy-assignment operator is an operator created by the compiler even if we don't define an operator=
and it assigns each non static member of the right side of the operand to the corresponding member in the left hand
operand using the copy-assignment operator of that class.

Exercise 13.7: What happens when we assign one StrBlob to another?
What about StrBlobPtrs?

Answer:
In both cases we implement operator= and thus the synthesized copy-assignment operator will be used and so for StrBlob
the count of the shared_ptr will rise since we are calling it's assignment operator for data.
StrBlobPtrs assignment will call the weak_ptr operator and thus the count will not increment also curr is of primitive type
and it will just be copied.